The paper describes a competition on Autonomous Lifelong Machine Learning with Drift, which involves developing computer programs capable of solving supervised learning problems where the i.i.d. assumption does not hold. This is a topic that is relevant to several sub-fields of computer science, including machine learning (cs.LG), artificial intelligence (cs.AI), computer vision (cs.CV), neural networks (cs.NE), and natural language processing (cs.CL). However, given that the focus of the competition was on developing algorithms for lifelong learning, which is a sub-field of machine learning, cs.LG is the most likely category.
